summary: Lots of Sophie and Maisie interviews...
body:
Lots of Sophie and Maisie interviews…

Very interesting how we only see Sophie and Maisie together doing so many magazine covers and interviews. I was sure that their role would be huge in this finale season and I did not need those interviews to convince me.

But honestly, I feel very good about it because it means they really want us to focus on the Stark girls.

I expected so much more of Kit and Emilia interviews but they are not even playing that game anymore. I’m really surprised!

Arya never received the hate Sansa had and I’m so glad to finally show the GA that these girls are both important and that Sansa is not supposed to be hated! I do think that choosing Sophie and Maisie as the “main” faces for discussing the final season is completely deliberate and the goal is to get people use to see them together and being close just like their character will be.

And by hearing Maisie and Sophie talking a lot about Sansa, I hope some people will start to realize how important Sansa Stark always was in this beautiful story.

summary: Repeat after me. Arya challenging Jon and supporting Sansa doesn’t mean she loves her big brother any less.  Again.  Arya...
body:
Repeat after me.

Arya challenging Jon and supporting Sansa doesn’t mean she loves her big brother any less. 

Again.

Arya challenging Jon and supporting Sansa doesn’t mean she loves her big brother any less.

It just means that it’s been years and she has no idea what to expect from him because the brother she remembers would never have given Robb’s crown to a foreigner simply because he fell in love. So while she might give him the benefit of the doubt, it’s no surprise that she’ll be pissed at the situation.

body:
Valonqar

A theory I don’t like, and yet makes a lot of sense:

Valonqar according to Cersei means little brother. That’s why she thinks Tyrion will kill her. But what if she’s wrong. (What if we are wrong about Jaime if Tyrion is in fact a Targaryen?)

In Valyrian there are some words without gender. We can see that in the show with The Prince/Princess That Was Pomised. We’ll see if it remains true in the books. Some words are like dragons, both things at the same time.

What if this word has no gender? It would be little brother/sister.

Yes, Cersei pressumably has no sister. Agreed. But it is never stated that it means your little brother, just little brother. It could be anyone’s brother or sister, the only limitation is being younger.

So let’s assume the Valonqar is a little sister. The possibilities could be endless. But there is one obvious train of thought: Arya.

Think about it, Jon and Arya’s POV make a reference to this nickname at least once in almost every chapter. When you hear little sister you inmediately associate it with Arya.

So, what if she is the Valonqar? What if it has been in front of our eyes all this time?

Prophecies are treaky and everybody (including myself right now) tries to understand the meaning (which they never actually do, they always do it wrong) so they can avoid the future (which is never successfull and they often make their prophecies true facts by trying to avoid them: it’s their actions the ones who starts the clock).

To sum up, Arya might be the Valonqar and I am definitely not taking my own advice to not to try and understand a prophecy. I mean, what’s the fun in that?

Thoughts?

summary:
Arya Stark and the Four Wolves   

“You must listen, and listen well. For indeed you have a choice. You can flee and hide, and...
caption:
Arya Stark and the Four Wolves  

“You must listen, and listen well. For indeed you have a choice. You can flee and hide, and wait to be found. You can live out your days in terror, without meaning. Or you can take the harder choice, and you can save them.” Daughter of the Forest by Juliet Marillier

Once a princess named Arya lived with father and her four brothers. She was no proper lady; preferring to run through the woods to embroidery. But when an evil sorceress curses her brothers turning them into wolves Arya must flee her home. The only way to save her family is by stitching them each a shirt made of stinging nettles all without uttering a word. Its hard, bloody business but Arya possesses a fierce love for her pack and a determination to see this grim task to its end. On her journey Arya befriends a blacksmith called Gendry who seems to be the only person who can understand her without words. The two grow closer but time is running out and not just for Arya’s brothers.

summary: "She steals in on little mice feet, but a man hears," he said. How could he hear me? she wondered, and it seemed as if he heard...
body:
“She steals in on little mice feet, but a man hears,” he said. How could he hear me? she wondered, and it seemed as if he heard that as well. “The scuff of leather on stone sings loud as warhorns to a man with open ears. Clever girls go barefoot.”

Arya would wait until she heard him snoring, then creep barefoot up the servant’s stair, making no more noise than the mouse she’d been. 

this is so subtle and i love it. one little comment from jaqen about going barefoot and arya ditches the shoes. he tells her that the leather of her shoes is loud enough for him to hear and she immediately adds this new knowledge into her survival repertoire. arya’s constantly looking to make herself quicker and quieter and harder to catch
